{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534458"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:46:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:46:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14965"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14965"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.24,0.02,0.02,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114687"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7653"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14965"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96690"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"906"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4613"},{"type":"tags","id":"5630"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48129"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114687"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man is being monitored in the Intensive Care Unit following coronary artery bypass surgery. He has a medical history of ischaemic heart disease, hypercholesterolaemia, hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include aspirin, atorvastatin, amlodipine and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring nursing handover, he suddenly loses consciousness. The cardiac monitor shows ventricular fibrillation, and his radial arterial line shows no pulsatile activity. The emergency buzzer is pressed, and the resuscitation team arrives immediately with a defibrillator.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence chest compressions","Single defibrillation attempt then chest compressions","Give 1 mg adrenaline","Give 300 mg amiodarone","Three immediate defibrillation attempts"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a witnessed ventricular fibrillation (VF) arrest in a monitored intensive care unit. The key feature is that the arrest is witnessed, monitored, and a defibrillator is immediately available in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThree immediate defibrillation attempts\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct management for witnessed VF arrest in a monitored setting. This approach is different from unwitnessed arrests or arrests in unmonitored settings. The rationale is that early defibrillation is the most effective intervention for VF, and in a monitored setting, there is minimal delay between arrest and shock delivery. The use of three \u0022stacked\u0022 shocks is further emphasised by the Australian Resuscitation Council guidelines for VF arrest post cardiac surgery as it will have the further benefit of minimising the potential harm of manual compressions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUp to three stacked shocks should be considered in cardiac arrest with a shockable rhythm when:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe arrest is witnessed and monitored\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe defibrillator is immediately available (e.g. first shock able to be delivered within 20 seconds)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe time required for rhythm recognition and for recharging the defibrillator is short (i.e. \u003C10 seconds)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing chest compressions\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate in an unwitnessed arrest or after three unsuccessful shocks. However, in witnessed VF with immediate defibrillator availability, shocking takes priority over compressions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle defibrillation attempt then chest compressions\u003C/strong\u003E is the standard approach for unmonitored VF arrests, but in this monitored setting, three immediate (stacked) shocks are recommended before starting compressions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiving 1 mg adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the advanced life support algorithm but is not the first step in witnessed VF. Defibrillation takes priority as it directly addresses the underlying rhythm disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiving 300 mg amiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered after three unsuccessful shocks, along with adrenaline, as part of the standard cardiac arrest protocol. It is not the first-line treatment for VF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter three unsuccessful shocks, the team should commence standard cardiac arrest management including high-quality chest compressions, ventilation, adrenaline, and consideration of reversible causes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Up to three stacked shocks should be considered in witnessed, monitored ventricular fibrillation arrest when a defibrillator is immediately available.","Stacked shocks in monitored VF arrest increase the chance of successful defibrillation compared to single shock followed by CPR.","After three unsuccessful shocks, standard cardiac arrest protocol with chest compressions should commence."],"references":["Australian and New Zealand Committee on Resuscitation (ANZCOR), 2024. Resuscitation in special circumstances (Guideline 11.10). Retrieved from: https://www.anzcor.org/home/adult-advanced-life-support/guideline-11-10-resuscitation-in-special-circumstances/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96690"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14965"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96690"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T16:17:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T16:20:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7653"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114687"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":n